article.description:
Deanna Nolan scored 19 points and
Cheryl Ford added a double-double as the Shock clinched
home-court advantage in the first round of the WNBA playoffs with
an 88-65 victory over the Sun on Sunday.
article.headline: Shock beat Sun, earn home court for first round
article.linkText: Shock eclipse Sun, earn home court for opening round
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- The last time the Detroit Shock had
home-court advantage in a playoff series, they won the 2003 WNBA
title.

They are hoping things go that well three years later.

Deanna Nolan scored 19 points and Cheryl Ford added a
double-double as the Shock clinched home-court advantage in the
first round with an 88-65 victory over the Connecticut Sun on
Sunday on the last day of the regular season.

"It's going to be nice to have home court again," Nolan said.
"It's been a long time."

The Sun, with the East's top seed wrapped up, rested All-Star
starters Lindsey Whalen and Katie Douglas and limited the playing
time of their other regulars.

"This game meant a lot, lot more to them than to us," said
Nykesha Sales. "You still don't want to just go out there
lollygagging."

The Sun (26-8) will play Washington in the first round, while
the second-seeded Shock (23-11) will take on Indiana. Detroit and
Connecticut will both open the best-of-three series on the road.

"With our format starting on the road, we're going to have to
be really ready to play Friday night," Connecticut coach Mike
Thibault said.

Ford finished with 15 points and 12 boards in the game, and 363
rebounds for the season, breaking Yolanda Griffith's league record
of 357.

"They told me a few games ago that I was getting close, but I
wasn't paying that much attention," Ford said. "That's just what
I do. I rebound."

Ford is averaging 10.3 rebounds a game in her four-year career,
slightly higher than the 10.1 mark posted in 19 seasons by her
father, Karl Malone.

"She's the best rebounder in the league, obviously," Detroit
coach Bill Laimbeer said. "But the growth in her maturity this
year has been tremendous. It's a pleasure to watch."

Katie Smith added 18 points for the Shock, who got points from
10 players.

"This game meant nothing to them, so we took care of our
business," Smith said. "Now we've got home court, but we have to
play Game 1 on the road. It's odd the way that works."

Taj McWilliams-Franklin led the Sun with 13 points and Erin
Phillips added 12.

"We were shooting to try a lot of different things today,"
Thibault said. "Some went well, some went really badly."

Detroit took instant advantage of the shorthanded Sun, jumping
out to an 11-2 lead and holding a 26-10 advantage at the end of the
first period.

The Shock increased the margin to 20 early in the second, but
started falling back into their trademark sloppy habits, turning
the ball over seven times in the quarter.

Connecticut was within 42-34 at the half, but the Shock started
the third period with a 9-1 run to regain control.

"We just wanted to get out there and attack and stick it to
them," Nolan said.
